fields.description:
I haven't noticed this affecting service yet, but opening opening this ticket to note that we may be exceeding the ARP cache on the CLC during specific workloads. In this case w/ 80 VMs run in 80 subnets within a 10-15 minute period. Below is var/log/messages over the course of roughly  3-5 of these tests. 

CLC kernel vars...
{code}
[root@h-10 log]#  sysctl net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh1
net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh1 = 1024
[root@h-10 log]#  sysctl net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh2
net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh2 = 2048
[root@h-10 log]#  sysctl net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh3
net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh3 = 4096
{code} 

CLC /var/log/messages...
{code}

fields.summary: VPC - May be exceeding ARP cache on CLC (Neighbour Table Overflow)

comments.body:
This can degrade service,  EUCA-11531 is believed to be an example of this.  
The test described above ran roughly 400-500 VMs (w/ unique MACs) per hour on this system. Guessing the dynamic interfaces/network artifacts supporting the network for each VM is contributing to the overflow?  
I believe this cloud was operating under the params defined in EUCA_11353 as shown above. 
Suggesting this ticket and/or EUCA-11353 be used to define/redefine the suggested cache settings for VPC per size of cloud and expected workloads. 
Thanks!
-M
